Reordering of the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the U.S. Department of State, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and what the Iraqi people, with the help of the Americans, can now put in place - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could foster reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
It will, however, take its time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East take hold.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security, economic, and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning by the Americans and the entire world and thanks to the rapid, focused, and targeted intervention by the coalition forces during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less than anticipated.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but fortunately the announced major crisis has never materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. Food, water, and medicine supplies are sufficient in most cases or are at least improving.
The American government has made approximately 600 million dollars available through the UN and NGOs for immediate humanitarian aid.
Moreover, we must restore the basic order in Iraq.
Security is an indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work, or go back to school.
After Saddam's fall, a wave of looting, lawlessness, and reckoning ensued.
Now it is the top priority to bring an end to this violence.
In addition, it must be the task of international troops to ensure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors further exacerbate the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures so that they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more precisely as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected, and modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of raw materials to process in Iraq.
The USA provide more than 2 billion dollars to support the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production is raised to a better level.
Long-term challenges include increasing oil production and reducing Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision by the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographic, and political divisions within Iraqi society, assisting in the political renewal of Iraq is undoubtedly the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq in which the rule of law is respected and the government comes about democratically - is not a utopia, especially because Iraq has an educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue on the chosen course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported in order to utilize the enormous political potential for constructive decisions.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have an impact on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any foreign policy issue that engages and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian question.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the United States developed a roadmap that brings us closer to this goal in stages.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to set this process in motion and take measures to improve the situation, in order to subsequently address broader issues at the negotiation table.
Finally, it cannot be acceptable that terrorists render the peace process futile for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically also a solution to all the problems of the Middle East.
The challenges that Iran presents to us are clear and unmistakable. This country develops weapons of mass destruction and supports terrorism.
Such actions defy the norms and rules of the international community and isolate Iran and its people.
If Iran continues in this manner, it will have consequences.
If Iran, however, turns away from terrorism and the development of catastrophic weapons, the United States is ready to resume good relations with this country.
Just as the United States is ready to engage with Syria if substantial changes in attitude can be achieved there.
A rather general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
For too long, America tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to advocate for a representative form of government.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the United States, the West, and the entire world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the Middle East Partnership Initiative launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
As shown in last year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), the Arab countries of the Middle East lag far behind other regions in the areas of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
For too long have these countries had to watch as economic growth passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If his recently proposed idea of a free trade zone between the United States and the Middle East were realized within a decade, it would provide a solid foundation for such development.
